=E2=80=9Cleading manufacturer and distributor of bathtubs and showers in Ca=
nada.=E2=80=9D The bonds were distressed =E2=80=94=C2=A0MAAX eventually wen=
t bankrupt in 2008 =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Harbinger started buying them at arou=
nd 50 cents on the dollar.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in the summe=
r of 2006, the Harbinger analyst on the trade =E2=80=9Cbegan hearing rumors=
 that there was aggressive short selling in the MAAX zips,=E2=80=9D led by =
one of Harbinger=E2=80=99s own prime brokerage firms. And in fact the prime=
 broker had a proprietary trader who=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>short the zips.=
 (This was in 2006, when big banks had proprietary traders.) =E2=80=9CFalco=
ne was angered by this,=E2=80=9D upset that his prime broker was =E2=80=9Cu=
ndercutting the value of his MAAX position and possibly borrowing his own n=
otes to cover its short position.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;"> <span>[1]</span> </a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To get re=
venge, Falcone decided to buy up all the zips. Actually more than all of th=
em: =E2=80=9CBy October 24, 2006, the Harbinger funds had purchased more th=
an the entire issue of the MAAX zips =E2=80=94 its position now stood at 17=
4 million in face value in a 170 million bond issue=E2=80=9D; by January 20=
07 it was at $192.6 million in face value, or 113% of the bonds. It could d=
o that because, again, other people were short: Short sellers own <em>negat=
ive</em> bonds, so if Falcone owned 193 million bonds, other people owned 3=
7 million, and short sellers were short 60 million, the math would work.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a></p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Sometime in the spring of 2007, Harbinger, at Falcone's direction, paid off=
 the debt in its margin account and demanded that the Wall Street firm retu=
rn any securities it had borrowed, including MAAX zips.</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =E2=80=9CWall Street firm=E2=80=9D (Harbinger=
=E2=80=99s prime broker who was also short the zips) couldn=E2=80=99t find =
any zips to deliver, because =E2=80=9CHarbinger was the only<br/>source of =
the notes =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0it had purchased more than the enti=
re issue and had locked up the bonds=E2=80=9D at a bank in Georgia. Harbing=
er offered to sell zips to the Wall Street firm=C2=A0at 100 cents on the do=
llar, but that price seemed ludicrously=C2=A0high =E2=80=94=C2=A0at that po=
int=C2=A0Harbinger itself<em>=C2=A0</em>had the bonds marked at 40 =E2=80=
=9Cdue to the current market in the senior debt and the deteriorating state=
 of the company's finances=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0so the bank said no.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It kept trying to find bonds, things ge=
t more awkward, and then in September 2007 Falcone had one of the coolest c=
onversations in the history of financial markets. A senior officer at the W=
all Street firm =E2=80=9Ccalled Falcone to discuss the situation with the M=
