the short squeeze began, and sufficiently in advance of the dividend=E2=80=
=99s record date.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the cour=
t agrees=C2=A0(citations omitted):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">The Supreme Court has interpreted =E2=80=9Cmanipulation=E2=80=9D to be =
=E2=80=9Cvirtually a term of art when used in connection with securities ma=
rkets.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The term generally refers =E2=80=9Cto practices, such =
as wash sales, matched orders, or rigged prices, that are intended to misle=
ad investors by artificially affecting market activity,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cconnotes intentional or willful conduct designed to deceive or defraud i=
nvestors by controlling or artificially affecting the price of securities.=
=E2=80=9D Whether an open-market transaction may qualify as a manipulative =
act is an issue of first impression for this court. Consistent with the Sec=
ond Circuit=E2=80=99s approach, we hold that an open-market transaction may=
=C2=A0qualify as manipulative conduct, but only if accompanied by plausibly=
 alleged deception. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Acting in a m=
anner that results in an artificial price, on its own, is not enough to con=
stitute manipulative conduct. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0For market activity to =E2=80=
=9Cartificially=E2=80=9D affect the price of securities, the manipulative c=
onduct must be =E2=80=9Caimed at deceiving investors as to how other market=
 participants have valued a security.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Here, Defendants=E2=80=
=99 truthful disclosure of the terms of the upcoming dividend transaction d=
id not deceive investors as to how the market valued Overstock.</p></blockq=
