nancial technologies embedded there in the idea of a check, the idea that w=
riting a number down on a piece of paper could create money. Well, not=C2=
=A0<em>create=C2=A0</em>money. You have some money at the bank, and the che=
ck is an instruction for the bank to move the money. It is an impressively =
minimal instruction that is widely accepted as money.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Of course it is not the most technologically sophisticated way t=
o move money,=C2=A0<em>now</em>. Now what you probably do is go to some web=
site or app run by your bank, and you log in with some credentials so the a=
pp knows it=E2=80=99s you, and the app can look up how much money is in you=
r account, and then you put your instructions into the app, and the bank mo=
ves the money. Or crypto found a way to do that stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0checki=
ng credentials, checking that the money is in your account =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
n a decentralized way. But none of this was technologically feasible 100 ye=
ars ago. Whereas =E2=80=9Cwrite the instructions on paper=E2=80=9D is so st=
raightforward and flexible.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously thoug=
